@@pInn of Lantern Rain@@N~
The Inn of Lantern Rain is Kowloon's oldest continuously operating lodging house, built on a flood-refuge platform that sheltered delta survivors during the Ashfall Monsoon years. The common room occupies the ground floor, its heavy timber ceiling beams hung with dozens of small oil @@planterns@@N whose warm light gives the inn its name and creates an atmosphere of amber intimacy. Wooden tables scarred by years of hard use fill the floor space, and a long serving counter runs the length of the back wall where the innkeeper dispenses meals, drinks, and room keys with equal efficiency. The walls are decorated with framed navigation charts, faded ferry tokens, and the personal effects of notable guests who stayed under this roof during pivotal moments in the city's history. The inn's stone foundation still bears the high-water marks of three successive monsoon floods, each line labeled with a date that residents of the southern quarter memorize as children. A narrow staircase in the corner leads to the upper-floor sleeping rooms, their doors fitted with the same sturdy locks used throughout the city's Warden-secured premises.

