@@RThe Iron Gate@@N~
The @@RIron Gate@@N is Kowloon's southern threshold, the busiest and most heavily defended of the city's four entrances. Massive timber doors reinforced with iron bands and backed by a secondary portcullis stand beneath a gatehouse arch bristling with observation slits, arrow loops, and the bronze speaking tubes that connect the gate watch to the wall command post. Warden checkpoints operate inside and outside the threshold, their inspection tables permanently staffed by guards who examine every traveler, vehicle, and cargo manifest with the practiced thoroughness of soldiers who know that this gate faces the lawless wetland frontier. The @@Riron portcullis@@N that gives the gate its name is visible overhead, its massive grating dark with oil and the weight of decades of security, ready to drop at the first signal of attack. The gate's stonework bears the scars of at least three historical assaults, each repaired but left deliberately visible as a reminder that the southern approach has been tested and held. A carved inscription above the inner arch mirrors the Jade Gate's northern counterpart: one wall, one law.

